00:23:11.931 --> 00:23:16.352
- What's the matter?
- Oh, it's chilly in here, that's all.

214
00:23:22.441 --> 00:23:25.319
- Want one?
- Oh, sure, I love Oreos.

215
00:23:25.486 --> 00:23:28.781
At home I eat them with--
I eat them with peanut butter.

216
00:23:28.948 --> 00:23:33.369
You do?
That is so weird. So do l.

217
00:23:33.535 --> 00:23:36.914
You're kidding. Most people
find that totally disgusting.

218
00:23:37.081 --> 00:23:38.958
I know.
I don't get it.

219
00:23:39.124 --> 00:23:41.377
Me either.

220
00:23:44.922 --> 00:23:46.757
What's your
dad like?

221
00:23:46.924 --> 00:23:48.968
I mean, is he the kind of father
you can talk to,

222
00:23:49.134 --> 00:23:51.845
or is he one of those
workaholic types who says,
"I'll talk to ya later, honey,"

223
00:23:52.012 --> 00:23:53.847
but, you know,
never really does?

224
00:23:54.014 --> 00:23:56.976
- I hate that.
- I don't have a father, actually.

225
00:23:57.142 --> 00:23:59.853
I mean, I had one once,
I suppose.

226
00:24:00.020 --> 00:24:02.606
But my parents
divorced years ago.

227
00:24:02.773 --> 00:24:04.942
My mother never even
mentions him.

228
00:24:05.109 --> 00:24:08.028
It's like he evaporated
into thin air or something.

229
00:24:08.195 --> 00:24:11.115
It's scary the way nobody
stays together any more.

230
00:24:11.282 --> 00:24:14.201
- Tell me about it.
- How old are you?

231
00:24:14.368 --> 00:24:17.538
- I'll be 12 on October 11.

232
00:24:17.705 --> 00:24:20.958
- So will I.
- Your birthday's on October 11?

233
00:24:21.125 --> 00:24:23.252
- Yeah.
- How weird is that?

234
00:24:23.419 --> 00:24:25.963
Extremely.

235
00:24:26.130 --> 00:24:28.257
Oh, hey.
It stopped raining.

236
00:24:28.424 --> 00:24:31.969
You wanna go get
a Popsicle or something?

237
00:24:39.268 --> 00:24:43.022
- What's the matter?
- Hallie, what's your mother like?

238
00:24:43.188 --> 00:24:48.318
I never met her. She and my dad split
up when I was a baby, maybe even before.

239
00:24:48.485 --> 00:24:51.363
I'm not sure.
He doesn't like to talk about her.

240
00:24:51.530 --> 00:24:54.033
But I know she was
really, really beautiful.

241
00:24:54.199 --> 00:24:56.618
How do you know that?

242
00:24:56.785 --> 00:25:00.831
Well, because my dad
had this old picture of her
hidden in his sock drawer,

243
00:25:00.998 --> 00:25:04.835
and he caught me looking at it,
like, all the time,
so he gave it to me to keep.

244
00:25:05.002 --> 00:25:08.756
Look, I'm-l'm really thirsty.
Sure you don't want to go to
the mess hall and get a lemonade?

245
00:25:08.922 --> 00:25:12.342
Will you stop thinking about
your stomach at a time like this?

246
00:25:12.509 --> 00:25:15.179
- At a time like what?
- Don't you realize what's happening?

247
00:25:17.014 --> 00:25:19.099
I mean,
think about it.

248
00:25:19.266 --> 00:25:21.101
I only
have a mother,

249
00:25:21.268 --> 00:25:23.312
and you only have
a father.

250
00:25:23.479 --> 00:25:25.314
You've never seen
your mom,

251
00:25:25.481 --> 00:25:27.608
and I've never
seen my dad.

252
00:25:27.775 --> 00:25:30.110
You have one old picture
of your mom,

253
00:25:30.277 --> 00:25:32.696
and I have one old picture
of my dad.

254
00:25:32.863 --> 00:25:35.324
But at least yours
is probably a whole picture.

255
00:25:35.491 --> 00:25:37.451
Mine is a pathetic
little thing,

256
00:25:37.618 --> 00:25:39.828
all crinkled and ripped
right down the middle and--

257
00:25:39.995 --> 00:25:43.665
What are you rummaging
in your trunk for?

258
00:25:43.832 --> 00:25:46.043
This.

259
00:25:46.210 --> 00:25:48.045
It's a picture
of my mom,

260
00:25:48.212 --> 00:25:50.047
and it's
ripped too.

261
00:25:50.214 --> 00:25:52.549
Right down
the middle?

262
00:25:52.716 --> 00:25:54.927
Right down
the middle.

263
00:26:12.069 --> 00:26:15.322
This is so...
freaky.

264
00:26:16.949 --> 00:26:18.784
Okay.

265
00:26:18.951 --> 00:26:22.120
On the count of three,
we'll show them to each other, okay?

266
00:26:22.287 --> 00:26:24.498
Okay.

267
00:26:24.665 --> 00:26:26.750
One.

268
00:26:26.917 --> 00:26:29.378
Two.

269
00:26:29.545 --> 00:26:31.421
- Three.
- Three.

270
00:26:38.220 --> 00:26:41.640
- That's my dad.
- That's my mom.

271
00:26:43.809 --> 00:26:45.644
That's the lunch bell.

272
00:26:45.811 --> 00:26:49.064
I'm not so
hungry any more.

273
00:26:50.274 --> 00:26:52.943
So if--
if your mom...

274
00:26:53.068 --> 00:26:55.320
is my mom...

275
00:26:55.487 --> 00:26:58.198
and my dad
is your dad...

276
00:26:58.365 --> 00:27:02.202
and we're both born on October 11...

277
00:27:02.369 --> 00:27:04.204
then you and I
are like--

278
00:27:04.371 --> 00:27:06.248
like sisters.

279
00:27:06.415 --> 00:27:08.250
Sisters?

280
00:27:08.417 --> 00:27:11.295
Hallie, we're
like twins.

281
00:27:19.970 --> 00:27:22.431
I just don't know what to say.

282
00:27:22.597 --> 00:27:24.433
What's that
you're holding?

283
00:27:24.599 --> 00:27:27.269
My locket.
I got it when I was born.

284
00:27:27.436 --> 00:27:29.521
It has an "H"
on it.

285
00:27:29.688 --> 00:27:32.733
[ Chuckles ]
I got mine when I was born, too,

286
00:27:32.899 --> 00:27:36.653
except mine has
an "A" on it.

287
00:27:36.820 --> 00:27:39.865
Ooh, now I've got goose bumps.

288
00:27:40.032 --> 00:27:42.534
My God, so I'm
not an only child.

289
00:27:42.701 --> 00:27:45.746
I'm a twin.
I'm a twin-- there's two of me.

290
00:27:45.912 --> 00:27:47.748
I mean,
two of us.

291
00:27:47.914 --> 00:27:49.916
- This is like--
- Mind boggling.

292
00:27:50.083 --> 00:27:52.586
- Totally.
- Completely.

293
00:27:52.753 --> 00:27:55.964
- Oh, my God.
- Oh, my God.

294
00:28:01.303 --> 00:28:04.181
Tell me, what's Mom like?

295
00:28:04.347 --> 00:28:08.185
Well, she designs wedding gowns.

296
00:28:08.351 --> 00:28:10.854
Really?

297
00:28:11.021 --> 00:28:13.356
She's becoming
quite famous, actually.

298
00:28:13.523 --> 00:28:16.651
A princess in Greece
just bought one of her gowns.

299
00:28:16.818 --> 00:28:18.653
Wow.

300
00:28:18.820 --> 00:28:21.531
Y-You know what's
interesting?

301
00:28:21.698 --> 00:28:25.035
Neither one of our parents
ever got married again.

302
00:28:25.202 --> 00:28:27.412
Has Dad ever been close
to getting remarried?

303
00:28:27.579 --> 00:28:32.209
Never. He always says
I'm the only girl in his life.

304
00:28:32.375 --> 00:28:34.377
Yeah, Mom's never
come close either.

305
00:28:41.760 --> 00:28:44.554
I have a brilliant,
beyond brilliant idea.

306
00:28:44.721 --> 00:28:47.140
I'm serious.
I am a total genius.

307
00:28:47.307 --> 00:28:49.601
You want to know
what Dad is like, right?

308
00:28:49.768 --> 00:28:51.603
Right.

309
00:28:51.770 --> 00:28:53.772
And I'm dying
to know Mom.

310
00:28:53.939 --> 00:28:56.316
So what I'm thinking is--
Don't freak out, okay?

311
00:28:56.483 --> 00:28:59.194
I think we should switch places.

312
00:28:59.361 --> 00:29:02.239
When camp's over
I'll go back to London as you,

313
00:29:02.405 --> 00:29:04.366
and you go back
to California as me.

314
00:29:04.533 --> 00:29:08.870
- What?
- Annie, we can pull it off.
We're twins, aren't we?

315
00:29:09.037 --> 00:29:12.290
Hallie, we're totally
and completely 100% different.

316
00:29:12.457 --> 00:29:14.960
So, what's the problem?
I'll teach you to be me...

317
00:29:15.126 --> 00:29:17.170
and you teach me
to be you.

318
00:29:17.337 --> 00:29:19.172
Look, I can
do you already.

319
00:29:19.339 --> 00:29:22.259
Yes, you want to know
the difference between us?

320
00:29:22.425 --> 00:29:24.427
I have class
and you don't.

321
00:29:24.594 --> 00:29:29.349
Come on, Ann. I got to meet my ma.

322
00:29:29.516 --> 00:29:32.644
The truth is, you know,
if we switch,

323
00:29:32.811 --> 00:29:36.398
sooner or later
they'll have to unswitch us.

324
00:29:36.565 --> 00:29:38.441
And when they do,
they'll have to meet again,

325
00:29:38.608 --> 00:29:41.987
- face to face.
- After all these years.

326
00:29:42.153 --> 00:29:46.616
Thank you. I told you
I'm brilliant.

327
00:29:46.783 --> 00:29:49.911
Okay. 'Tis grandfather.

328
00:29:50.078 --> 00:29:53.290
- He's so cute. What do we call him?
- Grandfather.

329
00:29:53.456 --> 00:29:55.792
Why didn't I think of that?

330
00:29:55.959 --> 00:29:58.044
This is Martin,
he's our butler.

331
00:29:58.211 --> 00:30:00.714
- We have a butler?
- Mm-hmm.

332
00:30:00.880 --> 00:30:04.092
Okay. Living-room's first.
Then over here is the dining room.

333
00:30:04.259 --> 00:30:06.303
But we never eat in there
except for Thanksgiving...

334
00:30:06.469 --> 00:30:08.888
and Christmas and,
of course, October 11.

335
00:30:30.285 --> 00:30:33.580
Okay. I-I'm ready.

336
00:30:55.435 --> 00:30:58.229
- Don't shut your eyes !
- Oh. Okay. Right.

337
00:30:58.396 --> 00:31:00.607
Sorry. Just got
a little nervous.

338
00:31:00.774 --> 00:31:03.443
You're nervous?
An 11-year-old is cutting my hair.

339
00:31:03.568 --> 00:31:05.487
Hey, you sounded just like me.

340
00:31:05.653 --> 00:31:09.532
Well, I'm supposed to, aren't I?
Go on, just do it.

341
00:31:13.912 --> 00:31:15.789
Don't panic.
You look great.

342
00:31:26.382 --> 00:31:28.218
Looking good.

343
00:31:31.888 --> 00:31:36.142
This is so... scary.

344
00:31:36.309 --> 00:31:39.270
Honey, you never
looked better.

345
00:31:39.437 --> 00:31:43.775
Oh, my God !

346
00:31:43.942 --> 00:31:45.777
What?

347
00:31:45.944 --> 00:31:47.779
I have
pierced ears.

348
00:31:47.946 --> 00:31:50.406
No. No, no and no.

349
00:31:50.573 --> 00:31:52.408
Not happening.
Sorry, wrong number.

350
00:31:52.575 --> 00:31:54.744
I won't.
I refuse.

351
00:31:54.911 --> 00:31:56.746
Then cutting your hair
was a total waste,

352
00:31:56.913 --> 00:31:58.748
'cause, I mean, there's no way
I can go to camp...

353
00:31:58.915 --> 00:32:00.750
with pierced ears
and come home without 'em.

354
00:32:00.917 --> 00:32:02.961
I mean, come on.
Get real.

355
00:32:18.852 --> 00:32:20.687
Needle sterilized.

356
00:32:20.854 --> 00:32:22.981
Y-You-- You sure you know
what you're doing?

357
00:32:23.147 --> 00:32:26.526
Relax. I've gone with all my friends
to get their ears pierced.

358
00:32:26.693 --> 00:32:29.362
It's nothing.
Just close your eyes,

359
00:32:29.487 --> 00:32:31.823
and it will be over
before you know it.

360
00:32:31.990 --> 00:32:35.201
- Earring ready?
- Yes.

361
00:32:35.368 --> 00:32:37.203
Good.
Hand me the apple.

362
00:32:39.789 --> 00:32:41.624
Thank you.

363
00:32:41.791 --> 00:32:44.586
Just relax. I'm telling you,
this is not a big deal.

364
00:32:44.752 --> 00:32:47.547
On the count of three,
remove the ice.

365
00:32:47.714 --> 00:32:50.925
One... two...

366
00:32:51.092 --> 00:32:53.219
three.

367
00:33:08.067 --> 00:33:10.361
Girls, time to say
your last goodbyes.

368
00:33:10.528 --> 00:33:13.072
- The busses are loading.
- Busses one and two leaving.

369
00:33:13.239 --> 00:33:16.075
I'll see you guys
next summer, I promise.

370
00:33:16.242 --> 00:33:19.037
Okay, so call me every single day.

371
00:33:19.203 --> 00:33:21.039
All right. And write me.
Don't forget.

372
00:33:21.205 --> 00:33:23.625
I won't.

373
00:33:23.791 --> 00:33:26.085
Okay. This is it.

374
00:33:26.252 --> 00:33:29.255
So remember, you're going
to find out how Mom and Dad met.

375
00:33:29.422 --> 00:33:32.175
- And you're going to find out
why they broke up.
- Annie James,

376
00:33:32.342 --> 00:33:35.011
- your car is here.
- That's you.

377
00:33:35.136 --> 00:33:38.139
Here's your ticket and passport.
Martin will pick you up
at the airport tomorrow morning.

378
00:33:38.306 --> 00:33:42.644
- What time do you leave?
- Oh, not for a couple of hours.
Give Mom a kiss for me.

379
00:33:42.810 --> 00:33:46.022
- Give Dad one for me.
- Annie James, front and centre.

380
00:33:46.189 --> 00:33:48.024
Bye.

381
00:33:48.191 --> 00:33:51.027
- Bye.
- Last call, Annie James.

382
00:33:55.865 --> 00:33:57.700
- Bye-bye.
- Bye.

383
00:34:05.208 --> 00:34:07.043
Good luck.

384
00:34:19.263 --> 00:34:23.810
Okay. This is it.

385
00:34:23.976 --> 00:34:26.854
God, I hope
she likes me.

386
00:34:27.021 --> 00:34:29.148
Please like me.

387
00:34:29.315 --> 00:34:31.150
Please.

388
00:35:02.181 --> 00:35:06.185
- Annie !
- Martin.

389
00:35:10.273 --> 00:35:12.650
- Missed you.
- Missed you.

390
00:35:12.817 --> 00:35:16.279
- What have you done to your hair?
- Cut it. Do you like it?

391
00:35:16.445 --> 00:35:19.532
Love it. It's the new you.

392
00:35:19.699 --> 00:35:21.534
And you've had
your ears pierced.

393
00:35:21.701 --> 00:35:23.619
Give me five,
girlfriend.

394
00:36:56.379 --> 00:36:59.090
- Home again.
- Thank you.

395
00:37:01.258 --> 00:37:04.762
This is it.
7 Primbrook Lane.

396
00:37:33.040 --> 00:37:35.751
Hello.

397
00:38:03.988 --> 00:38:06.449
Grandfather?

398
00:38:08.993 --> 00:38:12.997
- I'm home.
- Is that my little girl?

399
00:38:13.164 --> 00:38:15.833
That tall, gangly thing?

400
00:38:15.958 --> 00:38:18.335
Yes, it's me.

401
00:38:18.502 --> 00:38:22.965
Oh, welcome home.

402
00:38:23.132 --> 00:38:26.177
- Did you have a good time, sweet pea?
- Uh-huh, great.

403
00:38:26.343 --> 00:38:28.345
What are you doing?

404
00:38:28.512 --> 00:38:30.347
- Just smelling.
- Smelling?

405
00:38:30.514 --> 00:38:32.474
- I'm making a memory.
- Oh.

406
00:38:32.641 --> 00:38:34.643
Years from now,
when I'm all grown up,

407
00:38:34.810 --> 00:38:36.979
I'll always remember
my grandfather...

408
00:38:37.146 --> 00:38:39.273
and how he
always smelt of...

409
00:38:39.440 --> 00:38:41.442
peppermint
and pipe tobacco.

410
00:38:41.609 --> 00:38:43.444
Good to have you back.

411
00:38:43.611 --> 00:38:45.446
Annie?

412
00:38:50.326 --> 00:38:52.912
Annie?

413
00:38:54.121 --> 00:38:56.373
- Mother.
- You're back.

414
00:39:13.349 --> 00:39:16.685
- I can't believe it's you.
- And I can't believe
it's you.

415
00:39:16.852 --> 00:39:20.272
And with short hair.
Who cut it for you?

416
00:39:20.439 --> 00:39:23.359
A girl I met at camp.
Do you hate it?

417
00:39:23.525 --> 00:39:26.111
No, I absolutely
love it.

418
00:39:26.278 --> 00:39:29.448
You got your ears pierced?

419
00:39:29.615 --> 00:39:31.867
Well, are there any other surprises?

420
00:39:32.034 --> 00:39:35.037
Belly button rings,
tattoos?

421
00:39:35.204 --> 00:39:37.581
Ah, darling,
what is it?

422
00:39:37.748 --> 00:39:40.417
I'm sorry.
It's just--

423
00:39:40.542 --> 00:39:42.878
I've missed you
so much.

424
00:39:45.422 --> 00:39:47.257
I know.

425
00:39:47.424 --> 00:39:50.970
- It seems like it's been forever.
- You have no idea.

426
00:39:57.893 --> 00:40:01.647
So, come on. Tell me,
did you like everyone? Was it fun?

427
00:40:01.814 --> 00:40:06.235
- Ah, Martin.
- I found a stowaway in your suitcase.

428
00:40:06.402 --> 00:40:08.237
Oh, my God. Cuppy !

429
00:40:08.404 --> 00:40:10.739
- Cuppy?
- He-- He belongs to my friend,

430
00:40:10.906 --> 00:40:13.200
the one I was, umm,
telling you about.

431
00:40:13.367 --> 00:40:15.577
I can't imagine
how he got into my suitcase.

432
00:40:15.744 --> 00:40:19.289
Well, since he's not our Cuppy, shall
we dispose of the little creature?

433
00:40:19.456 --> 00:40:24.253
No ! I mean, no.
I'll-- I'll mail him to her.

434
00:40:24.420 --> 00:40:26.922
She loves this thing a lot--
a lot, a lot.

435
00:40:27.089 --> 00:40:29.133
And she's, like,
slept with this thing her entire life,

436
00:40:29.299 --> 00:40:33.262
And she could never be, like--
Stay in a foreign country without him.

437
00:40:33.429 --> 00:40:36.265
No, no. I'll take care of it.

438
00:40:36.432 --> 00:40:39.476
That will be all, Martin.
Thank you.

439
00:40:39.643 --> 00:40:41.937
Hello.

440
00:40:42.104 --> 00:40:44.940
Oh, hi.
How's the photo shoot going?

441
00:40:49.278 --> 00:40:53.240
Hmm. Well, can't you
manage without me?

442
00:40:53.407 --> 00:40:55.742
I mean, Annie just
got home from camp.

443
00:40:57.453 --> 00:40:59.288
Hmm. Yeah.

444
00:41:19.725 --> 00:41:24.688
Okay. Hold on a moment.

445
00:41:24.855 --> 00:41:29.067
Annie, would you hate very much
running down to the studio with me?

446
00:41:29.234 --> 00:41:32.154
No, I'd love it.

447
00:42:09.983 --> 00:42:14.029
Wow. That's incredible.
You designed that?

448
00:42:14.196 --> 00:42:17.032
Well, I had to do something
while you were at camp.

449
00:42:17.199 --> 00:42:20.911
- You don't think it's too--
- No, it's gorgeous. I love it.

450
00:42:21.078 --> 00:42:24.414
You know who would look
really beautiful in that gown?

451
00:42:24.581 --> 00:42:27.125
- I mean, like, really beautiful?
- Who?

452
00:42:27.292 --> 00:42:29.211
- You.
- Me?

453
00:42:29.378 --> 00:42:32.089
You know what? I think that time
change has made you a little loopy.

454
00:42:32.256 --> 00:42:34.549
Come on. Let's see
what all the fuss is about.

455
00:42:34.716 --> 00:42:36.551
Okay. I'm here.

